<div id="review_3391120890" class="review" itemprop="reviews" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Review">
  <link itemprop="url" href="https://www.goodreads.com/review/show/3391120890" />
    <a title="Tom A." class="left imgcol" href="/user/show/73137504-tom-a"><img alt="Tom A." src="https://images.gr-assets.com/users/1618773362p2/73137504.jpg" /></a>

  <div class="left bodycol">
    <div class="reviewHeader uitext stacked">
        <a class="reviewDate createdAt right" href="/review/show/3391120890?book_show_action=true">Jun 14, 2020</a>

      <span itemprop="author" itemscope itemtype="http://schema.org/Person">
        <a title="Tom A." class="user" itemprop="url" name="Tom A." href="/user/show/73137504-tom-a">Tom A.</a>
      </span>

        rated it
        <span class=" staticStars notranslate" title="really liked it"><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10">really liked it</span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p10"></span><span size="15x15" class="staticStar p0"></span></span>



        

    </div>


        <div class="reviewText stacked">
              <span id="reviewTextContainer3391120890" class="readable"
              >
            
<span id="freeTextContainer5821781452591490857"><b> Plague Review 15: Masks by Fumiko Enchi </b><br/><br/>A chance encounter between Ibuki and Mikame rekindles their shared love for the widowed Yasuko. But this also brings both of them into the clutches of Yasuko&apos;s mother-in-law Mieko, the Togano family matriarch with sinister motives. As the story progresses, both Ibuki and Mikame will find their destinies manipulated by Mieko. But how is Mieko accomplishing her plans, and what does it have to do with her endless fascination and obsession with Spirit Possess</span>
  <span id="freeText5821781452591490857" style="display:none"><b> Plague Review 15: Masks by Fumiko Enchi </b><br /><br />A chance encounter between Ibuki and Mikame rekindles their shared love for the widowed Yasuko. But this also brings both of them into the clutches of Yasuko's mother-in-law Mieko, the Togano family matriarch with sinister motives. As the story progresses, both Ibuki and Mikame will find their destinies manipulated by Mieko. But how is Mieko accomplishing her plans, and what does it have to do with her endless fascination and obsession with Spirit Possession and No theatre?<br /><br />My synopsis might have given the impression that this is a supernatural/ghost chiller but it's not. This is a more of a family revenge-drama filled to the brim with references to <a href="https://www.goodreads.com/book/show/7042.The_Tale_of_Genji" title="The Tale of Genji by Murasaki Shikibu" rel="nofollow noopener">The Tale of Genji</a> as well as discussions on Japanese Shamanism and Spirit Possession. This might hinder your enjoyment so beware.<br /><br />You know what's truly scary about <i> Masks </i>? It's being made an unwilling tool for someone's revenge against a perceived societal wrong. This is the horror in the book and when the reason behind this is revealed, you may find it justified concerning certain events in the story. But that doesn't make the actions of some characters less appalling.<br /><br />The writing is clear and engaging enough but the pace slackens due to the frequent insertions of discussions on different No Masks as well as the hidden themes in the aforementioned Tale of Genji. Enchi flirts with horror, too, conjuring horrific imagery in a flashback where a search party attempts to find Yasuko's husband in the snowy debris of Mt. Fuji. Let's just say the "face on the door while someone is on the other side with an ax" schtick gets a Japanese makeover. There are also depictions of shaman spirit possession, as well as a startling supernatural experience of one of the characters<br /><br />Having discussed these horror genre points of interest, however, the fact remains that this is not a quick and breezy read for the evening; this is a demanding piece of work despite the easy-going prose style of Enchi.<br /><br />Did I enjoy it? Not as much as I wanted to. But I did appreciate the complex themes as well as the characters acting toward their demise without their knowing. All life's a stage but be thankful you're not in the one these characters inhabit.</span>
  <a data-text-id="5821781452591490857" href="#" onclick="swapContent($(this));; return false;">...more</a>

          </span>
        </div>


